butch and trans identities. Acknowledging a younger generation of queer and trans people who are straining against the images foisted upon them, including this film’s egregious violence, and an older cohort for whom it remains a formative, if complicated, touchstone, Joynt and Page revisit the original contexts of production and distribution to unsettle the overdetermined ways the work has been understood and interpreted.Boys Don’t Cry ultimately relocates the film in a way that attends to the story’s violence and values, both on and off screen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTransgender people in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aBrandon Teena.  aHilary Swank.  abutch.  acinema.  aclass.  ahate-crimes.  ahollywo od.  akimberly peirce.  algbtq.  amedia.  aqueer.  arace.  arepresentation.  atransexual menace.  atransgender.  atransmasculinity.  aviolence.  awhiteness.1 aPage, Morgan M, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801300640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228013006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228013006/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles